<section xml:id="SECTIONvertical-asymptotes">
  <title>Vertical Asymptotes: <q>Infinite</q> Limits</title>

  <p>
    It should be clear from the sketch below that in addition to
    the horizontal asymptote <m>y=0</m>, the graph of <m>y=\frac1x</m> also
    has a vertical asymptote of <m>x=0</m>.
  </p>
  <image source="DC/VerticalAsymp3.png" width="50%"/>

  <p>
    We can extend the ideas and the notation we<rsq/>ve developed for
    horizontal asymptotes to handle vertical asymptotes as well. First
    note that since the expression <m>\frac1x</m> is not defined for <m>x=0</m> we
    can<rsq/>t talk about the behavior of the function at zero. But we
    can talk about its behavior near zero, and notice the graph is very
    different depending on whether <m>x\lt0</m> or <m>x\gt0</m>.  We will focus
    first on positive values of <m>x</m>.
  </p>
  <p>

    For <m>x</m> near zero, and positive, it is very clear what is happening.
    As <m>x\rightarrow0</m> the function continues to increase without bound.
    We capture this notationally with
    <men xml:id="EQUATIONRightHandLimit">
      
      \limitX{x}{0}{\frac1x}{x\gt0}=\infty.
    </men>
  </p>
  <aside>
    <title>Mathematical Notation</title>
    <p>
      The notation in <xref ref="EQUATIONRightHandLimit">equation</xref>
      is not standard. As far as we (the authors) know, it is not used
      in 
      any other textbook. The standard notation is
      <me>\limit{x}{0^+}{\frac1x}</me>. We think ours is superior and
      we<rsq/>re hoping it will catch on.
    </p>
  </aside>

  <p>
    <idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>limit</h><h>right<ndash/>hand</h></idx>
    The limit in <xref ref="EQUATIONRightHandLimit">equation</xref> is called a
    <term>right<ndash/>hand limit</term> and is read aloud as <q>the limit as <m>x</m>
    approaches zero from the right, of one over <m>x</m> equals infinity.</q>
  </p>
  <p>


    The expression
    <m>x\rightarrow0</m> means that <m>x</m>  is approaching the number zero. The
    qualification <m>x\gt0</m> specifies that it is approaching from the right.
    So writing<m>\limitX{x}{0}{\frac1x}{x\gt0}=\infty</m>  means 
    that as <m>x\rightarrow0</m> from the right, the function <m>\frac1x</m>
    increases without bound.
  </p>
  <!-- <aside> -->
  <!-- <title>Mathematical Notation</title> -->
  <!-- <p> -->
  <!--   The expression <m>\limitX{x}{0}{\frac1x}{x\gt0}=\infty</m> should -->
  <!--   probably be written as <m>\limitX{x}{0}{\frac1x}{x\gt0}\rightarrow -->
  <!-- \infty</m> but sadly, it has become standard to say, and to write, -->
  <!-- that this limit <q>equals infinity,</q> which is absurd. -->
  <!-- </p> -->
  <!-- </aside> -->

  <p>
    <idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>limit</h><h>left<ndash/>hand</h></idx>
    <idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>limit</h><h>one<ndash/>sided</h></idx>
    If we restrict <m>x</m>  to negative values then we see that
    <men  xml:id="EQUATIONLeftHandLimit">
      
      \limitX{x}{0}{\frac1x}{x\lt 0}=-\infty.
    </men>
    Note that the sense of the inequality has changed from <xref
    ref="EQUATIONRightHandLimit">equation</xref>. It is now <m>x\lt
    0</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    The limit in <xref ref="EQUATIONLeftHandLimit">equation</xref> is called a
    <term>left<ndash/>hand limit</term> and is read aloud as <q>the limit as <m>x</m>
    approaches zero from the left, of one over <m>x</m> equals negative infinity.</q> Right-
    and left-hand limits are generically called <term>one-sided
    limits</term>. One-sided limits are important theoretical tools but their
    theoretical value is not important to us right now. We will
    discuss them in more depth in <xref ref="SECTIONone-sided-deriv">Section</xref>.
  </p>
  <p>

    A function <m>f(x)</m>, will have a vertical asymptote as <m>x\rightarrow a</m>
    if either of the one-sided limits is <m>\infty</m> or <m>-\infty</m> (<m>f(x)</m> is
    increasing or decreasing without bound). We formalize this statement
    in the following definition.
  </p>
  <p>

  </p>

  <definition xml:id="DEFINITIONVerticalAsymptotes">
    <title>Vertical Asymptotes</title>
    <idx><h>Definition</h><h>Vertical Asymptotes</h></idx>
    <statement>
      <p>
        
        If
        <md>
          <mrow>
            \rlimit{x}{a}{f(x)}=\pm\infty\amp{}\amp{} \text{ or }\amp{}\amp{}\llimit{x}{a}{f(x)}=\pm\infty
          </mrow>
        </md>
        then the line <m>x=a</m> is a vertical
        asymptote of the graph of <m>y=f(x)</m>.

      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>



  <problem>
    <p>
      Compute each of the following limits. Read the notation
      carefully.
      <ol cols="2" marker="(i)">
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\rtlimit{x}{3}{\frac{1}{(x-1)(x-3)}}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\ltlimit{x}{3}{\frac{1}{(x-1)(x-3)}}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\ltlimit{x}{1}{\frac{1}{(x-1)(x-3)}}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\rtlimit{x}{1}{\frac{1}{(x-1)(x-3)}}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\rtlimit{x}{\frac{\pi}{2}}{\tan(x)}</m>
         </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\ltlimit{x}{\frac{\pi}{2}}{\tan(x)}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\ltlimit{x}{\frac{\pi}{2}}{\sec(x)}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\rtlimit{x}{\frac{\pi}{2}}{\sec(x)}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        </ol>
    </p>

  </problem>
  <exercise>
