      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>f(x)= \sec(x)</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <paragraphs>
    <title>One-Sided  Limits vs.  Limits</title>
    <p>
      Notice that so far in this section  we have only discussed one-sided
      limits like
      
      <md>
        <mrow>
          \llimit{x}{a}{f(x)} =\pm\infty \amp{}\amp{} \text{and}
          \amp{}\amp{}\rlimit{x}{a}{f(x)}=\pm\infty,
        </mrow>
      </md>
      but we have carefully avoided assigning any meaning to a
      formula like 

      <mdn>
        <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONPosNegInfLimits">
          \limit{x}{a}{f(x)}=\infty \amp{}\amp{} \text{or} \amp{}\amp{}
          \limit{x}{a}{f(x)}=-\infty.
        </mrow>
      </mdn>

      This is not because the topic is inherently
      difficult.  We<rsq/>re just  not quite ready to     discuss it
      yet.
    </p>
    <p>
      In fact, at this point you can probably guess the meanings of the
      expressions in  <xref
      ref="EQUATIONPosNegInfLimits">formula</xref> without any help
      from us.
    </p>
    <problem  xml:id="DRILLPosNegInfLimitsThrow">
      <p>
        Write down as clearly as you can what you believe the expressions
        <m> \limit{x}{a}{f(x)}=\infty </m> and <m>
        \limit{x}{a}{f(x)}=-\infty </m>
        mean and hold on to
        your answer. We will return to this topic in <xref
        ref="DRILLPosNegInfLimitsCatch"></xref>. When we get there
        you can compare your (educated) guess with our definition.
      </p>
    </problem>

  </paragraphs>
</section>

<section xml:id="SECTIONIndetFormsAndLhop">
  <title>Indeterminate Forms and L<rsq/>Hôpital<rsq/>s Rule</title>
  <subsection  xml:id="SUBSECTIONLHopitalsRule">
    <title>L<rsq/>Hôpital<rsq/>s Rule</title>


    <p>
      Based on our experience so far it is tempting to conclude that we
      can locate vertical asymptotes by simply setting the denominator
      equal to zero and solving.  But this is a naive conclusion as we
      will see next.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="EXAMPLEVertAsymp">
      <p>
        Consider <m>y=\frac{x-2}{x^2-4}</m>.  Setting the denominator equal
        to zero yields <m>x=-2</m> and <m>x=2</m>, but only one of these is
        a vertical asymptote. Do you see which one?

      </p>

      <p>
        Let<rsq/>s take a careful look at this example.  By
        <xref ref="DEFINITIONVerticalAsymptotes">Definition</xref> we will have a vertical
        asymptote when either one-sided limit of a function increases or
        decreases without bound, so we must evaluate each one-sided limit.
      </p>

      <p>
        For <m>x=-2</m>, we have
        <md>
          <mrow>\limitX{x}{-2}{\frac{x-2}{x^2-4}}{x\gt -2}
          \amp{}=\limitX{x}{-2}{\frac{x-2}{(x-2)(x+2)}}{x\gt -2}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp{}=\limitX{x}{-2}{\cancelto{=1}{\left(\frac{x-2}{x-2}\right)}}{x\gt -2}\,\,\cdot\,\,\limitX{x}{-2}{\frac{1}{x+2}}{x\gt -2}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp{}= 1\cdot\frac{1}{\approach{0}} =\infty</mrow>
        </md>
        So the line <m>x=-2</m> is indeed a vertical asymptote.
      </p>
    </example>

    <problem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Explain how you know the limit in <xref ref="EXAMPLEVertAsymp"></xref>  is not <m>-\infty</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </problem>

    <p>
      Similarly
      <mdn>
        <mrow  xml:id="EQUATIONSimpleLimit">\limitX{x}{-2}{\frac{x-2}{x^2-4}}{x\lt -2}
        \amp{}=\limitX{x}{-2}{\frac{x-2}{(x-2)(x+2)}}{x\lt -2}</mrow>
        <mrow number="no">\amp{}=\limitX{x}{-2}{\cancelto{=1}{\left(\frac{x-2}{x-2}\right)}}{x\lt -2}\,\,\cdot\,\,\limitX{x}{-2}{\frac{1}{x+2}}{x\lt -2}</mrow>
        <mrow number="no">\amp{}= 1\cdot\frac{1}{\approach{0}}=-\infty.</mrow>
      </mdn>
    </p>

    <problem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Explain how you know the limit in <xref ref="EQUATIONSimpleLimit">equation</xref>  is not <m>\infty</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </problem>

    <p>
      We were careful to use one-sided limits to find the vertical
      asymptote at <m>x= -2</m> because this is what <xref
      ref="DEFINITIONVerticalAsymptotes"></xref> calls for. Strictly
      speaking we only needed one of them, but since these limits were not
      equal we evaluated them both.
    </p>

    <p>
      However, for <m>x=2</m>, both one-sided limits are the same so we
      have
      <md>
        <mrow>\limit{x}{2}{\frac{x-2}{x^2-4}}=\limit{x}{2}{\frac{x-2}{(x-2)(x+2)}}
        \amp{}=\cancelto{=1}{\left(\limit{x}{2}{\frac{x-2}{x-2}}\right)}\,\,\cdot\,\,\left(\limit{x}{2}{\frac{1}{x+2}}\right)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp{}=\approach{1}\cdot\approach{\frac14}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp{}=\frac{1}{4}.</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <problem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Confirm <m>\tlimitX{x}{2}{\frac{x-2}{x^2-4}}{x\gt2}=\frac14</m> and
          <m>\tlimitX{x}{2}{\frac{x-2}{x^2-4}}{x\lt2}=\frac14</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </problem>

    <p>
      Observe that this limit has the form
      <m>\limit{x}{2}{\frac{x-2}{x^2-4}}=\frac{\approach{0}}{\approach{0}}</m>.
      A limit of this form is  another <term>indeterminate
      Form</term>  like <m>\approach{\infty -\infty }</m>.
    </p>
    <aside>
      <title>Comment</title>
      <p>
We
will encounter them later in this chapter. Remember that
<q>indeterminate</q> does not mean undefined. It means that they must
be addressed on a case<ndash/>by<ndash/>case basis, and their value is
often surprising. For example, would you have guessed that
<m>\limit{x}{2}{\frac{x-2}{x^2-4}}=2</m>?
      </p>
    </aside>

    <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMvertical-asymptotes">
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Find all vertical asymptotes of the graphs of each of the
          following functions.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>f(x)= \frac{x+2}{x^2-4}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>f(x)= \frac{x-2}{x^2-4}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>f(x)= \frac{x-2}{x^2-5x+6}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>f(x)= \frac{x-3}{x^2-5x+6}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>f(x)= \frac{x}{x^3-1}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>f(x)= \frac{x^2-x}{x^4-1}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>
    <p>

      <xref ref="EXAMPLEVertAsymp"></xref> demonstrates that a function
      which does not exist at a point is a more general concept than a
      function with a vertical asymptote at a point. 
    </p>
    <aside>
      <title>Mathematical Terminology</title>
      <p>
        A function with a vertical asymptote fails to exist. but it fails in a
        very particular manner. It increases (or decreases) without
        bound. Speaking colloquially, we say that it 
        <q>blows up</q> at the point
      </p>
    </aside>

    <p>
      Notice that <m>g(x)=\frac{x-2}{x^2-4}</m> is undefined at both
      <m>x=2</m> and <m>x=-2</m>, but it only has an asymptote at
      <m>x=-2</m>.  It also displays something subtle about limits.  One
      would be tempted to say that
      <me>
        \frac{x-2}{x^2-4}=\frac{x-2}{(x-2)(x+2)}=\frac{1}{x+2},
      </me>
      and this is true when <m>x\neq2</m>.  However, if we graph the two
      functions, <m>g(x)=\frac{x-2}{x^2-4}</m> and
      <m>f(x)=\frac{1}{x+2}</m> we see that there is a small difference
      between them:
    </p>
    <image source="DC/lhopital2.png" width="80%" />

    
    <p>
      Do you see the difference?  The value of <m>g(2)</m> is
      not defined because <m>g(2)=\frac{2-2}{4-4}</m> and we get a zero
      denominator. But no such difficulty occurs with <m>f</m> because
      <m>f(2) = \frac{1}{2+2}=\frac14</m>.
    </p>
    <aside>
      <title>Comment</title>
      <p>
        This discussion is also a cautionary tale about the use of graphing
        technology. These two graphs appear to be identical when we use
        technology to graph them.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <p>
      So, when <m>x\neq2</m>, <m>g(x)</m> and <m>f(x)</m> are the exactly
      the same. But they disagree when <m>x=2</m>. More precisely
      <m>x=2</m> is not in the domain of <m>g(x)</m> but it is in the
      domain of <m>f(x)</m>. Since the domains differ they must be
      different functions and it is incorrect to write
      <m>\frac{x-2}{x^2-4}=\frac{1}{x+2}</m> even though it is true for
      all but one value of <m>x</m>.
    </p>



    <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMDiffSqLim">
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>a\neq0</m> is a real number.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find all vertical asymptotes of
            <m>f(x)=\frac{x-a}{x^2-a^2}</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Does your solution of part (a) still work when <m>a=0</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMFoliumOfDescartes2">
