              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\rtlimit{t}{-1}{y(t)}</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\ltlimit{t}{-1}{y(t)}</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\rtlimit{t}{-1}{\dfdx{y}{x}}</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\ltlimit{t}{-1}{\dfdx{y}{x}}</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>

            Is this consistent with the graph and the fact that <m>t</m>
            represents the slope from the origin to the point <m>(x,y)</m>?
            Explain. 
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      We found earlier that
      <m>\tlimit{x}{\infty}{\frac{\sin(x)}{x}}=0</m>, so the function
      <m>y=\frac{\sin(x)}{x}</m> must have a horizontal asymptote at
      <m>y=0</m>. Clearly <m>y=\frac{\sin(x)}{x}</m> is undefined at
      <m>x=0</m>.  Does its graph have a vertical asymptote at <m>x=0</m>?
      Take your best guess.
    </p>
    <p>
      To answer this question we need to evaluate the limit
      <m>\tlimit{x}{0}{\frac{\sin(x)}{x}}</m>. But how can we do that?  If
      we try the obvious ploy of just <q>plugging in</q> zero for <m>x</m>
      we get the indeterminate form
      <m>\frac{(\rightarrow0)}{(\rightarrow0)}</m>, and we know we need to
      proceed cautiously with an indeterminate form.
    </p>

    <p>
      From the graph of <m>\frac{\sin(x) }{x}</m> (in the sketch below) it
      would appear that <m>\frac{\sin(x)}{x}\rightarrow1</m> as
      <m>x\rightarrow0</m>. This is correct, but we<rsq/>ve learned to be
      wary of relying on graphs.  It would be best to evaluate the limit
      by another technique if possible.
    </p>
    <image source="DC/lhopital4.png" width="70%"/>

    <p>
      Can we apply some algebraic trick like we did in <xref ref="EXAMPLEVertAsymp"></xref>?
    </p>

    <p>
      It is hard to see what it would be.  There isn<rsq/>t much algebra
      we can do here.  If there were other trigonometric functions
      involved we might be able to employ some trigonometric identity in
      the numerator, but there just isn<rsq/>t much we can do with
      <m>\sin(x)</m>. This problem poses a bit more of a challenge than
      the indeterminate forms we have dealt with so far. We need a new
      idea.
    </p>

    <p>
      Since the <m>\sin(x)</m> isn<rsq/>t helping maybe we can replace it
      with something simpler. Seriously.  Give some thought to what might
      be a valid replacement before reading on. Remember that we<rsq/>re
      really only interested in values of <m>x</m> that are very close
      (infinitely close?) to zero.
    </p>

    <p>
      <idx><h>Principle of Local Linearity</h></idx>
      The <xref ref="DEFINITIONLocalLinearity">Principle of Local Linearity</xref>  says that the graph of a function
      and its tangent line are locally indistinguishable. Since we<rsq/>re
      only interested in values of <m>x</m> near zero <mdash/> locally
      around zero <mdash/> let<rsq/>s try replacing <m>\sin(x)</m> with
      its tangent line.
    </p>

    <problem xml:id="EXERCISESync1">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that the line tangent to <m>y=\sin(x)</m> at <m>x=0</m> is
          <m>y=x</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </problem>

    <p>
      Replacing <m>\sin(x)</m> with <m>x</m>, we have
      <me>
        \limit{x}{0}{\frac{\sin(x)}{x}}\overset{?}{=}
        \limit{x}{0}{\frac{x}{x}}=1
      </me>
      which is consistent with what we see in the graph above. Our idea is
      showing some promise.
    </p>
    <aside>
      <title>Comment</title>
      <p>
        We<rsq/>ve placed the question mark over the equals sign because we
        don<rsq/>t (yet) actually know that this is a valid
        approach. We<rsq/>re just trying out ideas at the moment.
      </p>
    </aside>


    <p>
      Let<rsq/>s try this again with
      <m>\tlimit{x}{2}{\frac{x^3-8}{x^2-4}}</m> which also has the
      indeterminate form <m>\frac{\approach{0}}{\approach{0}}</m>.
    </p>

    <problem>
      <p>
        <ol marker="(i)">
          <li>
            <p>
              Show that the equation of the line tangent to <m>f(x)=x^3-8</m> at
              <m>(2,0)</m> is: <m>y=12(x-2)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Show that the equation of the line tangent to
              <m>g(x)=x^2-4</m> at <m>(2,0)</m> is: <m>y=4(x-2).</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </problem>

    <p>

      Since we are evaluating the limit at <m>x=2</m> we will replace the
      numerator and denominator with their tangent lines at <m>x=2</m>:
      <me>
        \limit{x}{2}{\frac{x^3-8}{x^2-4}}\overset{?}{=}\limit{x}{2}{\frac{12(x-2)}{4(x-2)}}=\limit{x}{2}{\frac{12}{4}}=3.
      </me>
    </p>

    <p>
      For comparison we<rsq/>ll also evaluate this one by methods
      we<rsq/>ve used before. Specifically if we factor the numerator and
      denominator we get:
      <md>
        <mrow>    \limit{x}{2}{\frac{x^3-8}{x^2-4}}=
        \limit{x}{2}{\frac{\textcolor{red}{(x-2)}(x^2+2x+4)}{\textcolor{red}{(x-2)}(x+2)}}\amp{}=
        \limit{x}{2}{\frac{x^2+2x+4}{x+2}}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp{}=
        \frac{2^2+2\cdot2+4}{2+2}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp{}=\frac{12}{4}=3.</mrow>
      </md>
      which is consistent with what we found previously. Our idea seems to
      be holding up.
    </p>




    <p>
      Let<rsq/>s try one more. The limit
      <me>\limit{x}{0}{\frac{\tan(3x)}{\sin(2x)}}</me> also has the
      indeterminate form <m>\frac{(\rightarrow0)}{(\rightarrow0)}</m> so
      we<rsq/>ll need the tangent lines of the numerator and denominator
      at <m>x=0</m> again.
    </p>
    
    <problem>
      <p>
        <ol marker="(i)">
          <li>
            <p>
              Show that <m>y=3x</m> is the equation of the line tangent to <m>\tan(3x)</m>
              at <m>x=0</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Show that <m>y=2x</m> is the equation of the line tangent to
              <m>\sin{(2x)}</m> at <m>x=0</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </problem>
    
    <p>
      Replacing the numerator and denominator by their tangent lines at
      <m>x=0</m>, we get
      <me>
        \limit{x}{0}{\frac{\tan(3x)}{\sin(2x)}} \overset{?}{=}
        \limit{x}{0}{\frac{3x}{2x}} = \frac32.
      </me>
    </p>

    <problem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Graph the equation <m>y=\frac{\tan(3x)}{\sin(2x)}</m> and zoom
          in on the portion of the graph near <m>x=0</m>. Does it
          look like we<rsq/>ve found the correct limit?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </problem>



    <p>
      In all of our examples where the indeterminate form was a
      fraction,  replacing the numerator and denominator
      with their respective tangent lines seems to have worked. The
      idea seems promising so let<rsq/>s look at it in a more general
      context. If <m>f(x)</m> and <m>g(x)</m> are differentiable
      functions such that <m>f(a)=g(a)=0</m> then
      <m>\limit{x}{a}{\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}}</m> is an indeterminate form.
    </p>

    <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMTanLineArbFunc">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that the equations of the lines tangent to arbitrary
          differentiable functions, <m>f(x)</m> and
          <m>g(x)</m>, at <m>x=a</m> are 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              y=f(a)+f^\prime(a)(x-a) \amp{}\amp{}  \text{and} \amp{}\amp{}
              y=g(a)+g^\prime(a)(x-a).
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      <idx><h>Principle of Local Linearity</h></idx>
      If we replace <m>f(x)</m> and <m>g(x)</m> in <xref
      ref="PROBLEMTanLineArbFunc"></xref>  with their tangent lines
      at <m>x=a</m> we have
      <me>
        \limit{x}{a}{\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}}  =
        \limit{x}{a}{\frac{f(a)+f^\prime(a)(x-a)}{g(a)+g^\prime(a)(x-a)}}.
      </me>
      Since <m>f(a)=g(a)=0</m> we see that
      <me>
        \limit{x}{a}{\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}}  =
        \limit{x}{a}{\frac{0+f^\prime(a)(x-a)}{0+g^\prime(a)(x-a)}}.
      </me>
      So
      <men xml:id="EQUATIONLHV1">
        \limit{x}{a}{\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}} =
        \frac{f^\prime(a)}{g^\prime(a)}.
      </men>
      (We<rsq/>ll need to assume that
      <m>g^\prime(a)\neq0</m>. Do you see why?)

      This is consistent with all of our examples above so it appears that
      the <xref ref="DEFINITIONLocalLinearity">Principle of Local Linearity</xref>  has led us in the right direction.
      All of the evidence we<rsq/>ve gathered so far suggests rather strongly
      that when we are faced with the indeterminate form
      <m>\frac{(\rightarrow0)}{(\rightarrow0)}</m> simply replacing the numerator
      and denominator with their tangent lines will work.
    </p>

    <p>
      This idea is due to the Swiss mathematician <url
      href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Bernoulli_Johann/"
      visual="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Bernoulli_Johann/">Johann
      Bernoulli</url> (1667<ndash/>1748). Johann and his brother <url
      href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Bernoulli_Jacob/"
      visual="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Bernoulli_Jacob/">Jacob
      Bernoulli</url> (1665<ndash/>1795)  were taught Calculus by Leibniz
      himself, but soon showed themselves to be his equal, or nearly so.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <caption>
        <url href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Bernoulli_Johann/" visual="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Bernoulli_Johann/">Johann
        Bernoulli </url>(1667<ndash/>1748)
      </caption>
      <image source="DC/Bernoulli-Johann.png" width="30%"/>
    </figure>



    <p>
      The Marquis de L<rsq/>Hôpital, <url
      href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/De_LHopital/"
      visual="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/De_LHopital/">Guillaume
      François Antoine de L<rsq/>Hôpital<rsq/></url> was keenly interested
      in the new Calculus so he struck a deal with Johann. The Marquis
      agreed to pay Bernoulli to tutor him and to keep L<rsq/>Hôpital
      abreast of new mathematical developments. This was done with the
      understanding that L<rsq/>Hôpital would include some of
      Bernoulli<rsq/>s research results in the Calculus textbook
      L<rsq/>Hôpital was writing at the time. This turned out to be
      the very first Calculus textbook: 
      <url href="https://old.maa.org/press/periodicals/convergence/mathematical-treasure-l-hospital-s-analyse-des-infiniment-petits"  visual="https://old.maa.org/press/periodicals/convergence/mathematical-treasure-l-hospital-s-analyse-des-infiniment-petits"><pubtitle>Analyse
      des Infiniment Petits pour l<rsq/>Intelligence des Lignes Courbes
      (Analysis of the Infinitely Small for the Understanding of Curved
      Lines)</pubtitle></url>.  It was published in 1696.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <caption>
        <url href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/De_LHopital/" visual="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/De_LHopital/">The
        Marquis de L<rsq/>Hôpital </url> (1661<ndash/>1704)
      </caption>
      <image source="DC/De_LHopital.png" width="30%"/>
    </figure>

    <p>
      <idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>Hôpital<rsq/>s Rule</h></idx>
      Even though L<rsq/>Hôpital   acknowledged his indebtedness to Johann Bernoulli
      for this procedure it has always been known as
      <term>L<rsq/>Hôpital<rsq/>s Rule</term>.
    </p>
    <aside>
      <title>Pronunciation</title>
      <p>
        L<rsq/>Hôpital<rsq/>s name is pronounced LOW-Pea-Tall, not
        le-HOS-pital.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <p>
      As a mathematician L<rsq/>Hôpital was not in the same league as Leibniz,
      Newton, or the Bernoullis <mdash/> few are <mdash/>
      but he was a very competent mathematician and his work helped to
      disseminate the ideas of Calculus just as Maria Gaëtana Agnesi<rsq/>s
      text would do in the following century.
    </p>

    <p>
      Now look back at the examples in this section and notice the
      following fact: In each case when the limit was finally evaluated it
      turned out to be the slope of the line tangent to the graph of the
      numerator divided by the slope of the line tangent to the graph of
      the denominator. But the slope of the line tangent to <m>f(x)</m> at
      <m>x=a</m> is simply <m>\eval{\dfdx{y}{x} }{x}{a} = f^\prime(a)
      </m>.
    </p>
    <aside>
      <title>Mathematical Notation</title>
      <p>
        Recall that when  we introduced Lagrange<rsq/>s
        prime notation in <xref
        ref="SECTIONDerivative"></xref>
        we said that there are times when Lagrange<rsq/>s
        notation is much more convenient than differential
        notation. This is such a time. In this section we will be using
        Lagrange<rsq/>s notation exclusively to indicate derivatives.
        <m>f^\prime(a)</m>. 
      </p>
    </aside>

    <p>
      In light of <xref ref="EQUATIONLHV1">equation</xref> it appears that we don<rsq/>t need
      to go to the trouble of finding the tangent lines. We can evaluate
      these indeterminate forms as follows:
    </p>


    <theorem xml:id="THEOREMLHRule1">
      <title>L<rsq/>Hôpital<rsq/>s Rule, (First Special Case)</title>
      <idx><h>Theorem</h><h>L<rsq/>Hôpital<rsq/>s Rule</h><h>First Special Case</h></idx>
      <p>
        Suppose 
        <ol marker="(1)">
          <li>
            that <m>f(x)</m> and <m>g(x)</m> are differentiable on an
            open interval containing <m>a</m>,
          </li>
            <li> that
            <m>f(a)=g(a)=0</m>
            </li>
            <li>  that             <m>f^\prime(a)</m> and 
            <m>g^\prime(a)</m> are both defined.
            </li>
            <li>
              and that <m>g^\prime(a)\ne0 </m>,
            </li>
        </ol>
        Then
        <me>
          \limit{x}{a}{\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}}\lhopeq\frac{f^\prime(a)}{g^\prime(a)}
          </me>.
      </p>
    </theorem>
    <remark>
      <title>Mathematical Notation</title>
      <p>
        We will use the notation <me>A\lhopeq B</me> to indicate that
        <m>A</m> is equal to <m>B</m> as a result of  L<rsq/>Hôpital<rsq/>s
        Rule.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <p>
      <idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>Hôpital  Indeterminate</h></idx>
      Because L<rsq/>Hôpital<rsq/>s Rule applies directly to the indeterminate form
      <m>\frac{(\rightarrow0)}{(\rightarrow0)}</m> we will refer to this as a
      <term>L<rsq/>Hôpital  Indeterminate</term>. Not all
      indeterminate forms are  L<rsq/>Hôpital  Indeterminates.
    </p>

    <example>
      <p>
        Consider <m>\limit{x}{0}{\frac{\tan{x}}{x}}.</m>
        This is a L<rsq/>Hôpital indeterminate so
        <me>
          \limit{x}{0}{\frac{\tan(x)}{x}}\lhopeq\frac{\sec^2(0)}{1}=1.
        </me>
      </p>
    </example>


    <example>
      <p>
        Consider <m>\tlimit{x}{0}{\frac{\cos(x)-1}{x}}.</m>
        This is a  L<rsq/>Hôpital indeterminate so
        <me>
          \limit{x}{0}{\frac{\cos(x)-1}{x}}\lhopeq\frac{\sin(0)}{1}=0.
        </me>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      We want to emphasize very strongly that L<rsq/>Hôpital<rsq/>s
      Rule requires a L<rsq/>Hôpital indeterminate. If we don<rsq/>t
      have a L<rsq/>Hôpital indeterminate we can not use
      L<rsq/>Hôpital<rsq/>s Rule.  If you try to use
      L<rsq/>Hôpital<rsq/>s Rule when it does not apply, you will
      probably not get the correct answer.  The difficulty here is
      that nothing in the computations will alert you that anything
      has gone wrong. You have to be watchful for this potential
      pitfall.
    </p>

    <example>
      <p>
        For example, if we mistakenly try to use L<rsq/>Hôpital<rsq/>s Rule,
        on
        <m>
          \limit{x}{1}{\frac{x+1}{x+2}}
          </m> we
          will obtain <m>\limit{x}{1}{\frac{1}{1}}=1</m>, but this  is obviously
          incorrect.
      </p>
    </example>
    <problem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that <m>  \tlimit{x}{1}{\frac{x+1}{x+2}}=\frac23</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </problem>





    <problem>
      <p>
        Compute each of the following limits:
        <ol cols="3" marker="(i)">
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\tlimit{x}{1}{\frac{x(x-1)}{x^2-1}}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\tlimit{x}{2}{\frac{x(x-1)}{x^2-1}}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\tlimit{x}{\frac12}{\frac{6x^2+5x-4}{4x^2+16x-9}}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\tlimit{x}{0}{\frac{\cos(x) -1}{x}}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\tlimit{x}{1}{\frac{\ln(x) }{x-1}}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\tlimit{x}{e}{\frac{\ln(x^2) }{x+e}}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\tlimit{x}{1}{\frac{t^3-1}{t^4-1}}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\tlimit{x}{0}{\frac{\sin(3 x)}{\sin(7 x)}}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\tlimit{x}{0}{\frac{\cos(3 x)}{\cos(7 x)}}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\tlimit{x}{0}{\frac{\sin(4 x)}{\tan(5 x)}}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\tlimit{x}{0}{\frac{\inverse\tan(x)}{x}}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\tlimit{x}{0}{\frac{\inverse\cot(x)}{x}}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>

    </problem>
    <example>
      <p>
        <xref ref="THEOREMLHRule1"></xref>  is useful but it is much too limited, so
        to speak. For example, it does not help us with this limit:
        <m>\tlimit{x}{0}{\frac{\cos(3x)-1}{\cos(5x)-1}}</m>. Even though it is a L<rsq/>Hôpital
        indeterminate, when we apply   <xref ref="THEOREMLHRule1"></xref>  we have
        <me>
          \limit{x}{0}{\frac{\cos(3x)-1}{\cos(5x)-1}} \lhopeq
          {\frac{-3\sin(3\cdot0)}{-5\sin(5\cdot0)}} = \frac{0}{0}
        </me>
        This is useless because <m>\frac{0}{0}</m> is still not defined.

      </p>
      <p>
        
        We need to think about this again. It is true that <m>\frac{0}{0}</m> is
        not defined, but if
        <me>
          f^\prime(a)=\limit{x}{a}{f^\prime(x)}=0
        </me>
        and
        <me>
          g^\prime(a)=\limit{x}{a}{g^\prime(x)}=0.
        </me>
        then <m>\limit{x}{a}{\frac{f^\prime(x)}{g^\prime(x)}}</m> is a L<rsq/>Hôpital
        Indeterminate so we extend
        <xref ref="THEOREMLHRule1"></xref> as follows:
      </p>
    </example>






    <theorem xml:id="THEOREMLHRule2">
      <title>L<rsq/>Hôpital<rsq/>s Rule, (Second Special Case)</title>
      <idx><h>Theorem</h><h>L<rsq/>Hôpital<rsq/>s Rule</h><h>Second Special Case</h></idx>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>\limit{x}{a}{\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}}</m> is the L<rsq/>Hôpital
        Indeterminate form <m>\frac{(\rightarrow0)}{(\rightarrow0)}</m>. Then
        <me>
          \limit{x}{a}{\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}}=\limit{x}{a}{\frac{f^\prime(x)}{g^\prime(x)}}.
        </me>
      </p>
    </theorem>

    
    <p>  
      Our derivation of <xref ref="THEOREMLHRule2"></xref> is not entirely
      rigorous. We will not be providing a fully rigorous derivation of
      L<rsq/>Hôpital<rsq/>s Rule because doing so is both difficult to produce
      and to understand. There are deep foundational issues involved and
      investigating these would take us too far from our primary purpose,
      gaining proficiency with its use.

      Returning to our example and using <xref ref="THEOREMLHRule2"></xref> this time
      we have
      <me>
        \limit{x}{0}{\frac{\cos(3x)-1}{\cos(5x)-1}}
        \lhopeq\limit{x}{0}{\frac{-3\sin(3x)}{-5\sin(5x)}}.
      </me>
      The limit on the right is yet another L<rsq/>Hôpital Indeterminate so we
      apply L<rsq/>Hôpital<rsq/>s Rule again.
      <md>
        <mrow>
          \limit{x}{0}{\frac{\cos(3x)-1}{\cos(5x)-1}} \amp{} \lhopeq
          \limit{x}{0}{\frac{-3\sin(3x)}{-5\sin(5x)}}
        </mrow>
        <mrow> 
          \amp{} \lhopeq
          \frac35\limit{x}{0}{\frac{3\cos(3x)}{5\cos(5x)}}
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          \amp{} =  \frac35\cdot\frac{3\cos(0)}{5\cos(0)}
        </mrow>
        <mrow> 
          \amp{}=  \frac{9}{25}.
        </mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Use <xref ref="THEOREMLHRule2"></xref> to compute each of the
          following limits. If this limit given is not a L<rsq/>Hôpital
          Indeterminate rearrange it algebraically, without changing its
          value, until it is a L<rsq/>Hôpital Indeterminate.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\limit{x}{0}{\frac{e^x-1-x}{x^2}}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\limit{x}{0}{\frac{\cos(mx)-\cos(nx)}{x^2}}</m>. Assume that
